			<ns0:name>mcgra...@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/109286297231979736865/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">This is similar to issue 2238 and issue 2358 but for the MXCSR (SSE control/status word) rather than the x87 control word.

The TCB's value of the MXCSR leaks to untrusted code, which is an information leak but of pretty boring information.

It's also potentially an untrusted ABI violation, if any TCB or OS code changed the nonvolatile bits in the MXCSR, so that untrusted code's use of SSE FP might behave differently than it should.

More importantly, untrusted code's value of the MXCSR leaks back into trusted code, which could permit untrusted code to do something like enabling exceptions or change rounding behavior so that any TCB or OS code that uses SSE FP might behave differently than it should.
